I had booked a party of 20 for my mothers 90th birthday.  We booked it in December for today’s date and gave a deposit.  1 week ago I received an email that they made a mistake and rented the entire venue out.  They offered to move the party to the steak house but of course, no live jazz and not a brunch.  I think that they way they treated us was appalling.  No phone call, no other offer of reparations and didn’t care that we had 1 week to find another place to host my mothers birthday party.  I think that the management of Minton’s should be ashamed at having treated us so poorly.  The good news is that we had a GREAT brunch today at Red Rooster Ginnys Supper Club.  The show was amazing, the service was excellent, the food wonderful and they were so accommodating and helpful.  I highly recommend Ginnys - a first rate place.  And I would not go to Mintons - clearly they do not care about their customers and don’t know what they are doing.

Coming from Australia, I wasn't sure I would love a jazz lounge; I knew I'd enjoy it, but I was unsure as to the extent. But, oh sweet baby James...! This was the highlight of our trip to New York! If we hadn't come here on our last night in NYC I'd have been buying tickets to the next night's show on the way out the door! If you enjoy cool lighting, intimate atmospheres, and are open to jazz that slows and relaxes your soul, do yourself the favour and visit Minton's!
Nice attmosphere but very overpriced. I feel like the band could just keel over and die at anytime. Sleepy jazz, and they KNOW it...

If you truly enjoy jazz, Minton’s is a decent venue however they impose steep food and drink minimums for a reason. Service is horrendous. The staff are young teens who do not seem to have any hospitality experience.  Our waiter was nice but extremely slow and forgetful. We waited over 45 minutes for refills on our sangria (note: the sangria is not fresh or homemade and is poured out of a wine bottle label Sangria..). Water glasses were refilled randomly. We were a table of 14 and only two or three water glasses were refilled even though it was clear that several others were empty. At one point, a manager for one of the bands brought me a glass of water even though he did not work for the venue. The space is tight and warm.  They will add tables in the walkways and box you in making it impossible to move about or even get up to use the restroom. The food is decent as the kitchen is shared with Cecil’s but steer clear of the pasta dishes which are dry and lack flavor. The brownie a la mode is dry and not of good quality.  I’m not much of a jazz fan and only went for a birthday party but will steer clear of Minton’s moving forward. The service is truly shameful. I would never return.

There is no place else like this in New York City.  My father’s birthday was last August. My mother and I decided that we just had to have a party for him at Minton’s. We had been there a couple of times before and always had wonderful experiences.  So I contacted Minton’s and they were more than accommodating when I told them that I wanted to reserve a table for a large party (12 people).  Once we arrived, we were immediately seated in the front of the room, right near the band (as I had requested). From that point on, we were treated to great service, wonderful music and awesome food. My father was treated to a heartfelt “Happy Birthday” from the Minton’s staff, Manager and the Executive Chef.  I would also like to single out the band’s lead guitarist who made my father and the rest of my table feel like family.  I don’t know whether to say it’s the food, the people, or the music but there is something about Minton’s that makes it a wonderful place but I recommend that you experience it for yourself. I plan on going to Minton’s again and again.  P.S. I highly recommend the macaroni and cheese, the low country seafood. All desserts were awesome.

I brought my brother and met a girlfriend at Minton's this past Thursday night.  The dinner was good but the menu was very limited.  Not being a meat eater, there were limited options for seafood.  I ordered grits and shrimp separately a la carte.  My brother had the steak dinner which he said was the best steak he'd ever eaten, this says a lot because my brother is somewhat of a steak connoisseur.  My shrimp were actually prawns, nice and quite large and cooked to perfection.  Our dinner was $120, which included 2 glasses of wine.  We paid an additional $40 fee for the musicians who played for about 20 minutes during our stay.  I'd go back, but was mildly disappointed that I wasn't aware of the cover charge.
